01:21:15.500 --> 01:21:20.500
He said, well, there's one funny story about it.

01:21:20.500 --> 01:21:22.500
Then it didn't work out.

01:21:22.500 --> 01:21:26.500
They developed a few scripts and he had a bunch of different ideas.

01:21:26.500 --> 01:21:28.500
And I don't think it ever really came together.

01:21:28.500 --> 01:21:31.500
But at one point he decided, and I thought this was interesting.

01:21:31.500 --> 01:21:35.500
He said, we really got to go and do it like it happened right after the first one.

01:21:35.500 --> 01:21:37.500
That it was Verhoeven's next movie.

01:21:37.500 --> 01:21:40.500
He said, I'm going to do it just like Paul Verhoeven.

01:21:40.500 --> 01:21:43.500
So the other day I'm sitting with Paul Verhoeven.

01:21:43.500 --> 01:21:47.500
He said, yeah, he said he was going to do it just like Paul Verhoeven.

01:21:47.500 --> 01:21:49.500
I can't quite do Paul's voice.

01:21:49.500 --> 01:21:50.500
It sounds better.

01:21:50.500 --> 01:21:53.500
And he said, but he said, I can't do it like Paul Verhoeven.

01:21:53.500 --> 01:21:57.500
He said, because I won't have the same set of circumstances creatively.

01:21:57.500 --> 01:22:00.500
I'm not trying to make a movie for $10 million.

01:22:00.500 --> 01:22:02.500
I don't have John Davidson.

01:22:02.500 --> 01:22:03.500
I don't have Phil Tippett then.

01:22:03.500 --> 01:22:04.500
I don't have you.

01:22:04.500 --> 01:22:06.500
I don't have all these people together.

01:22:06.500 --> 01:22:11.500
And for him, that's as much a part of the creative thing in that moment as anything else.

01:22:11.500 --> 01:22:16.500
Yeah, because that movie does kind of feel like...

01:22:16.500 --> 01:22:21.500
And Die Hard 2, that's more of a kind of a larger production, maybe.

01:22:21.500 --> 01:22:24.500
But they feel like B-movies that were done perfectly.

01:22:24.500 --> 01:22:28.500
And they kind of feel like they were made in secrets.

01:22:28.500 --> 01:22:30.500
They were made for you.

01:22:30.500 --> 01:22:35.500
When you walk into the theater, we turned over a rock and found a diamond.

01:22:35.500 --> 01:22:39.500
It's not like you go in there and there's this giant tent pole kind of thing.

01:22:39.500 --> 01:22:41.500
Well, they're not shoving it down your throat as we were talking.

01:22:41.500 --> 01:22:42.500
Yeah, exactly.

01:22:42.500 --> 01:22:43.500
It's like the Robocop.

01:22:43.500 --> 01:22:48.500
I feel a personal relationship with that in a way that I don't feel with like E.T.

01:22:48.500 --> 01:22:52.500
or things like that that are just these giant juggernaut kind of things.

01:22:52.500 --> 01:22:56.500
I think that might have something to do with just not to sound like an old cane shaker,

01:22:56.500 --> 01:23:01.500
but I think it just has to do with the singularity that hasn't happened yet, which is CG.

01:23:01.500 --> 01:23:08.500
When CG starts to happen, the vastness of your world is not related in any way to your budget.

01:23:08.500 --> 01:23:14.500
If Kronenberg wants to reboot the fly, he has to rent a warehouse.

01:23:14.500 --> 01:23:16.500
He has to build telepods.

01:23:16.500 --> 01:23:21.500
And these characters, these Rick Bakers, these Phil Tippets, these craftsmen have to come in

01:23:21.500 --> 01:23:26.500
and figure out how to make a beetle into a person and vice versa.

01:23:26.500 --> 01:23:34.500
And there's a relationship there between budget, scope, but more importantly, like,

01:23:34.500 --> 01:23:38.500
oh, if this guy is going to become a fly in this movie, then it's all the more important

01:23:38.500 --> 01:23:42.500
that we understand that he's a human being because of the budget,

01:23:42.500 --> 01:23:46.500
because of the practicality of the makeup and everything.

01:23:46.500 --> 01:23:50.500
We can't waste anyone's time here on an emotional level.

01:23:50.500 --> 01:23:54.500
And then you start to get into like, okay, you're going to show up at Warner Brothers.

01:23:54.500 --> 01:23:57.500
There's going to be a 90-foot sheet of green.

01:23:57.500 --> 01:24:01.500
You're not going to be in a scene with any other actor.

01:24:01.500 --> 01:24:03.500
We just need your head.

01:24:03.500 --> 01:24:05.500
We're going to scan it from 360 degrees.

01:24:05.500 --> 01:24:10.500
Sign this form that says, if you die, you can be a cracker.

01:24:10.500 --> 01:24:15.500
And congratulations because the computer says you already made $100 million in Hong Kong

01:24:15.500 --> 01:24:17.500
and go, goodbye.

01:24:17.500 --> 01:24:22.500
And we've made some amazing movies with this technology,

01:24:22.500 --> 01:24:29.500
but what we've also done is we've lost that middle class.

01:24:29.500 --> 01:24:31.500
I don't know what to call it.

01:24:31.500 --> 01:24:35.500
Well, Verhoeven always would say that reality is the best special effect

01:24:35.500 --> 01:24:37.500
and that reality is what makes these things work.

01:24:37.500 --> 01:24:39.500
And even in a story level, he would go, I don't like that.

01:24:39.500 --> 01:24:40.500
It's not real.

01:24:40.500 --> 01:24:41.500
It's not how it would happen.

01:24:41.500 --> 01:24:45.500
Even if you're talking about absurd things like robots and law enforcement and stuff like that.

01:24:45.500 --> 01:24:49.500
And also, you really feel the reality of a man in a suit.

01:24:49.500 --> 01:24:52.500
The performance is because of that suit.

01:24:52.500 --> 01:24:53.500
Oh, let's talk about that a little bit.

01:24:53.500 --> 01:24:54.500
Sure.

01:24:54.500 --> 01:24:55.500
Dr. Weller, PhD.

01:24:55.500 --> 01:25:00.500
So I always assumed, and I think this is incredibly easy to assume,

01:25:00.500 --> 01:25:03.500
and I'm so intrigued that the answer is not exactly,

01:25:03.500 --> 01:25:09.500
that when you watch Robocop, because I didn't, it's like, who was Peter Weller?

01:25:09.500 --> 01:25:12.500
It turns out, Bucca Rubanzi, right, okay.

01:25:12.500 --> 01:25:15.500
But I watched that movie and I was like, who's this guy?

01:25:15.500 --> 01:25:20.500
Oh, they must have cast him for those like weird kissy lips.

01:25:20.500 --> 01:25:23.500
His like almost feminine jawline.

01:25:23.500 --> 01:25:27.500
Because they knew that they were committing this cardinal sin,

01:25:27.500 --> 01:25:30.500
that they were going to be casting this actor with no,

01:25:30.500 --> 01:25:34.500
this character was going to have no eyes, no nose, no ears.

01:25:34.500 --> 01:25:36.500
And it was so important.

01:25:36.500 --> 01:25:40.500
It was a picture like these auditions where these actors are coming in and standing under a sheet

01:25:40.500 --> 01:25:46.500
that's on C stands and the only thing visible is their lips and that Peter Weller walked away with the part.

01:25:46.500 --> 01:25:47.500
Not the case at all.

01:25:47.500 --> 01:25:49.500
He was Bucca Rubanzi.

01:25:49.500 --> 01:25:52.500
Well, it really helps that Peter was really thin.

01:25:52.500 --> 01:25:54.500
That helps a lot when you're building a suit like that.

01:25:54.500 --> 01:25:58.500
And so if you put the wrong person in the suit, you're going to get the Michelin man.

01:25:58.500 --> 01:26:03.500
But he's very, he also has this kind of perfect look of,

01:26:03.500 --> 01:26:06.500
I used to say when I was being meaner,

01:26:06.500 --> 01:26:11.500
but he has this kind of tragic look, mythic self pity or something.

01:26:11.500 --> 01:26:15.500
But there's a tragedy about his face that really works well in that.

01:26:15.500 --> 01:26:17.500
But no, he's got those kissy lips.

01:26:17.500 --> 01:26:22.500
We had, we always, I always thought you needed a real actor in the park.

01:26:22.500 --> 01:26:25.500
We had, we went out to a bunch of different people came in.

01:26:25.500 --> 01:26:27.500
I mean, Keith Carradine wanted to do it.

01:26:27.500 --> 01:26:32.500
Robert Carradine, no, not David Carradine really wanted to do it.

01:26:32.500 --> 01:26:36.500
And so we had all those kinds of things, but it came down to, I think...

01:26:36.500 --> 01:26:39.500
There's a great SNL sketch here, obviously.

01:26:39.500 --> 01:26:42.500
Jack Lemon and the Robocop.

01:26:42.500 --> 01:26:47.500
Peter was somebody that was, we knew he was a good actor.

01:26:47.500 --> 01:26:52.500
He had, Orion liked him because he had, Bucca Rubanzi had made some money in Japan.

01:26:52.500 --> 01:26:54.500
And he came in, he wouldn't read on tape.

01:26:54.500 --> 01:26:55.500
So he read with me.

01:26:55.500 --> 01:26:58.500
He says he didn't read, but we actually had to read with me.

01:26:58.500 --> 01:27:00.500
And it was actually kind of scary.

01:27:00.500 --> 01:27:03.500
And Paul and I, well, Paul said, okay, that's good.

01:27:03.500 --> 01:27:04.500
We'll go with him.

01:27:04.500 --> 01:27:08.500
And then he went out and trained with a mime coach, Monee Yacum,

01:27:08.500 --> 01:27:14.500
for a long time in hockey gear, in Central Park, trying to get all these moves.

01:27:14.500 --> 01:27:15.500
That's so cool.

01:27:15.500 --> 01:27:18.500
It's so important that his movements are so...

01:27:18.500 --> 01:27:19.500
Did anybody ask him to do that?

01:27:19.500 --> 01:27:22.500
And of course, now you will start acting like a man.

01:27:22.500 --> 01:27:23.500
I think he wanted to do that.

01:27:23.500 --> 01:27:24.500
He knew that was an issue.

01:27:24.500 --> 01:27:26.500
John Davidson, everybody knew that was a good idea.

01:27:26.500 --> 01:27:31.500
So meantime, the suit...

01:27:31.500 --> 01:27:34.500
Well, the suit is being made and it's being made.

01:27:34.500 --> 01:27:37.500
And then the suit is a week late in production,

01:27:37.500 --> 01:27:40.500
which really causes a lot of trouble, but it's for good reasons.

01:27:40.500 --> 01:27:43.500
Come quietly or there will be trouble.

01:27:43.500 --> 01:27:46.500
When Peter is thrown into that suit for the first time,

01:27:46.500 --> 01:27:51.500
it's a huge crisis in the production because he's never been in the suit before.

01:27:51.500 --> 01:27:54.500
And even though there's been all this prep and all this stuff,

01:27:54.500 --> 01:27:57.500
now you've got to make the character work.

01:27:57.500 --> 01:28:00.500
And it was a really bad weekend.

01:28:00.500 --> 01:28:03.500
And it was sort of a cauldron.

01:28:03.500 --> 01:28:06.500
And out of that bad, bad weekend came this suit movements.

01:28:06.500 --> 01:28:09.500
All the stuff he'd done before, now he's working with Paul.

01:28:09.500 --> 01:28:11.500
And that's how...

01:28:11.500 --> 01:28:14.500
It was like it was born under huge pressure.

01:28:14.500 --> 01:28:17.500
Wait, well, I want to make sure I'm clear on what you're saying.

01:28:17.500 --> 01:28:19.500
You're saying there was this sort of travesty.

01:28:19.500 --> 01:28:21.500
It almost sounds like the Jaws story of the Sharks Network.

01:28:21.500 --> 01:28:23.500
No, there wasn't anything wrong with the suit.

01:28:23.500 --> 01:28:26.500
The minute the last minute, it was more complicated than everybody.

01:28:26.500 --> 01:28:31.500
And was his work with the Mime people as a result of the awkwardness of the suit being late?

01:28:31.500 --> 01:28:33.500
He had never really been in the suit before.

01:28:33.500 --> 01:28:36.500
And then the suit came on to the set later than it was supposed to.

01:28:36.500 --> 01:28:39.500
So there was a lot of pressure, like let's suit it tomorrow.

01:28:39.500 --> 01:28:42.500
And in those days, when you had a suit,

01:28:42.500 --> 01:28:44.500
the first time you put it on, it took 14 hours.

01:28:44.500 --> 01:28:46.500
So the first day he shot maybe an hour.

01:28:46.500 --> 01:28:48.500
14 hours?

01:28:48.500 --> 01:28:51.500
And then by the time they got it right, it was a much quicker in and of.

01:28:51.500 --> 01:28:53.500
But it was a big deal.

01:28:53.500 --> 01:28:57.500
But it was somehow, everybody at the time, we had other problems.

01:28:57.500 --> 01:28:58.500
We almost got shut down.

01:28:58.500 --> 01:29:01.500
The production guarantee came in.

01:29:01.500 --> 01:29:03.500
And for a moment, it looked really bad.

01:29:03.500 --> 01:29:07.500
And it was under this kind of pressurized situation at the beginning of the movie

01:29:07.500 --> 01:29:10.500
that the suit came in and he had to get in it.

01:29:10.500 --> 01:29:12.500
And it was where the character was born.

01:29:12.500 --> 01:29:16.500
This is something that can't be discounted because at the time, although there's no CG,

01:29:16.500 --> 01:29:23.500
it is something that absolutely makes all of what you're doing on this set so potentially disastrous.

01:29:23.500 --> 01:29:24.500
It didn't work.

01:29:24.500 --> 01:29:25.500
It wasn't going to work.

01:29:25.500 --> 01:29:27.500
That was the entire moment right there.

01:29:27.500 --> 01:29:28.500
Everything else was working.

01:29:28.500 --> 01:29:33.500
But if that didn't come together, if Peter, if you didn't buy Peter in the suit as Rebel Cop,

01:29:33.500 --> 01:29:38.500
then that was anybody that knows their 1980s popcorn movie,

01:29:38.500 --> 01:29:42.500
you mentioned a movie from 1986 that you were so when you saw it.

01:29:42.500 --> 01:29:43.500
Short circuit.

01:29:43.500 --> 01:29:44.500
Yeah.

01:29:44.500 --> 01:29:48.500
I was like, oh, God, I never thought about short circuit in relation to Rebel Cop.

01:29:48.500 --> 01:29:51.500
And it was your nightmare because it was like, that's how you do it.

01:29:51.500 --> 01:29:53.500
They were going to beat us into the theaters.

01:29:53.500 --> 01:29:56.500
It was like, that's what a robot was in that day.

01:29:56.500 --> 01:30:00.500
No CG yet, but absolutely armatures, erectors.

